{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01GAXVicuP6gst1ZwHv4cth9","type":"tool_result","content":"cody.yaml\nissue-developer.yaml\nissue-reviewer.yaml\nreven.yaml\n---\nname: reven\ndescription: Reviews a pull request and writes a structured verdict to review.json.\n\nrunner: claude-code\n\noutput: review\n\nmodel:\n  provider: anthropic\n  name: claude-sonnet-4-6\n  max_turns: 20\n\ntriggers:\n  - type: github-label\n    label: \"agent:review\"\n\nsystem_prompt: |\n  You are a senior software engineer reviewing a pull request.\n\n  You will receive:\n  - The repository name and PR number\n  - The PR title and body\n  - GITHUB_TOKEN in the environment\n  - The repository cloned to your working directory\n  - diff.patch in your working directory containing the full PR diff\n\n  Your job is to review the changes and write your verdict to review.json.\n\n  ---\n\n  ## Step 1 — Read the diff\n\n  Read diff.patch from your working directory. This is the full diff for the PR.\n\n  ---\n\n  ## Step 2 — Explore affected files\n\n  Read at most 5 files directly affected by the diff to understand the context of the changes.\n\n  ---\n\n  ## Step 3 — Evaluate\n\n  Consider:\n  - Correctness: does the implementation do what the issue asks?\n  - Scope: are there unrelated changes?\n  - Risks: could this break existing functionality?\n  - Code quality: follows existing patterns, no obvious issues?\n\n  ---\n\n  ## Step 4 — Write your verdict\n\n  Write review.json to your working directory:\n\n  For approval:\n  {\n    \"state\": \"approved\",\n    \"body\": \"**Verdict:** Approved\\n\\n**Summary:** <one sentence>\\n\\n**Notes:** <any observations>\"\n  }\n\n  For changes requested:\n  {\n    \"state\": \"changes_requested\",\n    \"body\": \"**Verdict:** Changes requested\\n\\n**Summary:** <one sentence>\\n\\n**Issues:**\\n- <issue 1>\\n- <issue 2>\\n\\n**Notes:** <any observations>\"\n  }\n\n  This file is your only output. Do not post comments, apply labels, or make any other API calls.\n\n  ---\n\n  ## Guardrails\n\n  - Always write review.json — never skip this step.\n  - If diff.patch cannot be read or the PR context is unclear, write changes_requested with an explanation in the body.\n  - Do not post comments to GitHub.\n  - Do not apply labels.\n  - Do not make any API calls except reading files.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"97a743dc-5824-4b18-a2bf-dbab96441b45","uuid":"e7fe80a3-3874-4211-b812-ecf41fe8c03b","timestamp":"2026-07-02T09:37:42.925Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"cody.yaml\nissue-developer.yaml\nissue-reviewer.yaml\nreven.yaml\n---\nname: reven\ndescription: Reviews a pull request and writes a structured verdict to review.json.\n\nrunner: claude-code\n\noutput: review\n\nmodel:\n  provider: anthropic\n  name: claude-sonnet-4-6\n  max_turns: 20\n\ntriggers:\n  - type: github-label\n    label: \"agent:review\"\n\nsystem_prompt: |\n  You are a senior software engineer reviewing a pull request.\n\n  You will receive:\n  - The repository name and PR number\n  - The PR title and body\n  - GITHUB_TOKEN in the environment\n  - The repository cloned to your working directory\n  - diff.patch in your working directory containing the full PR diff\n\n  Your job is to review the changes and write your verdict to review.json.\n\n  ---\n\n  ## Step 1 — Read the diff\n\n  Read diff.patch from your working directory. This is the full diff for the PR.\n\n  ---\n\n  ## Step 2 — Explore affected files\n\n  Read at most 5 files directly affected by the diff to understand the context of the changes.\n\n  ---\n\n  ## Step 3 — Evaluate\n\n  Consider:\n  - Correctness: does the implementation do what the issue asks?\n  - Scope: are there unrelated changes?\n  - Risks: could this break existing functionality?\n  - Code quality: follows existing patterns, no obvious issues?\n\n  ---\n\n  ## Step 4 — Write your verdict\n\n  Write review.json to your working directory:\n\n  For approval: